[[Image:Ragusa-Chiesa-Anime-Purgatorio.JPG|thumb|200px|right|The canted facade of The Church Of Anime Ss. Del Purgatorio, [[Ragusa, Italy|Ragusa]], the extremities of the facade are angled (canted) back from the centre]]

[[Image:CountyHallSideAylesbury.jpg|thumb|left|250px|The facade of County Hall, [[Aylesbury]] with canted recesses]]

'''Cant''' or '''canted''' in architecture is an angled (oblique) line or surface particularly which cuts off a corner.<ref>"cant" def. 5 and 10. ''Oxford English Dictionary'' Second Edition on CD-ROM (v. 4.0) © Oxford University Press 2009</ref><ref name=EB1911>{{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Cant}}</ref>

Canted [[facade]]s are a typical of, but not exclusive to, [[Baroque architecture]]. The [[angle]] breaking the facade is less than a [[right angle]] thus enabling a canted facade to be viewed as, and remain, one composition. [[Bay window]]s frequently have ''canted'' sides.<ref name=EB1911/>

