{{Architecturalelement-stub}}

{{Other uses}}

'''Cut and run''' or '''cut-and-run''' is an [[idiom]]atic [[verb phrase]] meaning to "make off promptly" or to "hurry off". The phrase originated in the 1700s as describing an act allowing a ship to make sail quickly in an urgent situation, either by cutting free an anchor or by cutting ropeyarns to unfurl sails from the [[Yard (sailing)|yards]] on a [[square rig]] ship. Though initially referring to a literal act, the phrase was used figuratively by the mid-1800s in both the United States and England. The phrase is used as a [[pejorative]] in political language, implying a panicked and cowardly retreat, and it has been used by politicians in the United States, Great Britain, and Australia as a criticism of calls to withdraw troops, becoming particularly associated with the [[United States Republican Party]].

== Origin ==
To "cut and run" was defined by Englishman David Steel in 1794 as "to cut the cable and make sail instantly, without waiting to weigh anchor".{{sfn|Steel|2011|p=136}} He further described the practice as "quick but very expensive" but sometimes necessary, such as when the anchor is hooked on rocks and cannot be retrieved, in bad weather, when the anchor is on [[lee shore]] and the ship is in danger of [[embayment]], or when one must quickly escape or pursue an enemy; instead of cutting the anchor by axe at the [[hawsehole]], Steel offered an alternate method of slipping the anchor cable if time permitted, a method he felt wiser than cutting as it potentially prevented loss of anchor and cable.{{sfn|Steel|2011|p=70-71}} An alternate origin comes from the practice on [[square rig]] ships to furl the sails stopped to the [[Yard (sailing)|yards]] with ropeyarns so that the yarns may be cut to let the sails fall unfurled should an urgent need to sail arise.{{sfn|Kemp|1994|p=221}} The phrase was in use by the early 1700s, and ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' cited the earliest printed usage of the phrase to ''[[The Boston News-Letter]]'' in 1704.<ref name="OED">{{cite web |url=http://dictionary.oed.com/view/Entry/46341#eid7593967|title=cut, v. |year=1989 |work=[[Oxford English Dictionary]] |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |location=Oxford }} {{subscription required}}</ref>

== Usage ==
Though "cut and run" initially referred to a literal act, the phrase later appeared in figurative usage in ''[[White-Jacket]]'' (1850) by American author [[Herman Melville]] and in ''[[Great Expectations]]'' (1861) by English author [[Charles Dickens]].<ref name="OED" /><ref name="Safire">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/05/02/magazine/the-way-we-live-now-5-2-04-on-language-cut-and-run.html|title=The Way We Live Now: 5-2-04: On Language; Cut and Run|last=Safire|first=William|authorlink=William Safire|date=May 2, 2004|website=|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=June 11, 2016}}</ref> ''Oxford English Dictionary'' defines the figurative, colloquial usage as "to make off promptly" or to "hurry off".<ref name="OED" />

=== In politics ===
In May 2004, [[William Safire]] in ''[[The New York Times]]'' noted that the phrase, when used in reference to politics and war, lost its "lighthearted sense" and came to become a [[pejorative]] implying panic and "cowardice, going beyond an honorable surrender" and is "said in derogation of a policy to be opposed with the utmost repugnance".<ref name="Safire" /> [[Dana Milbank]] characterized the phrase as a [[slogan]] used by members of [[Republican Party (United States)|United States Republican Party]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/06/20/AR2006062001343.html|title=It's Time to Cut and Run From 'Cut and Run'|last=Milbank|first=Dana|authorlink=Dana Milbank|date=June 21, 2006|website=|publisher=''[[The Washington Post]]''|access-date=June 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wnyc.org/story/128686-cut-and-run/|title=Cut and Run|last=Pesca|first=Mike|authorlink=Mike Pesca|last2=Milbank|first2=Dana|authorlink2=Dana Milbank|date=June 23, 2006|website=On the Media|publisher=[[WNYC]]|access-date=June 11, 2016}}</ref> and in December 2015, [[Robert Entman]] identified the phrase as one of numerous [[meme]]s or slogans that "trigger a series of instant, clear mental associations" lending to the "communicative success" of the Republican Party.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Entman|first=Robert|author-link=Robert Entman|date=December 3, 2015|title=Framing and party competition: How Democrats enabled the GOP’s move to the uncompromising right|url=http://www.brookings.edu/~/media/research/files/papers/2015/12/03-framing-party-competition-entman/party_competition.pdf|journal=Issues in Governance Studies|publisher=[[Brookings Institution]]|issue=70|doi=|pmid=|access-date=June 11, 2016}}</ref> Linguist [[George Lakoff]] stated that the phrase is an example of the Republican Party's skill at "distilling an issue to a simple phrase" and analyzed the phrase as one that "presupposes that the opposite is to stand and fight".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://archive.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2006/06/21/gop_wants_cut_and_run_label_to_stick/|title=GOP wants 'cut and run' label to stick|last=Williams|first=Joseph|date=June 21, 2006|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|access-date=June 11, 2016|via=[[Boston.com]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref>

In the United States, the phrase saw usage by politicians as a criticism against calls to withdraw from the [[Lebanese Civil War]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/target/interviews/weinberger.html|title=Interview: Caspar Weinberger|last=|first=|date=September 2001|website=[[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|Frontline]]|publisher=[[PBS]]|access-date=June 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Every choice a bad choice|last=Kilpatrick|first=James|date=October 27, 1983|work=[[The Daily Register]]|quote=The alternative, in the short and ugly phrase, is to cut and run — to withdraw from the multinational peacekeeping force and to bring the Marines home. It is not an appealing alternative. Any such order would be interpreted universally as a pusillanimous act. It would be seen as a surrender to terrorists, and it would invite repetitions. The multinational force would be disbanded; diplomatic efforts at internal reconciliation would be set back; factional bloodshed would return. The result might be to carve up Lebanon and to serve most of it to Syria on a platter.|via=}}</ref> [[Vietnam War]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/15/opinion/the-man-who-said-no-to-war.html|title=The Man Who Said No to War|last=Herbert|first=Bob|authorlink=Bob Herbert|date=December 15, 2005|website=|publisher=''[[The New York Times]]''|access-date=June 11, 2016}}</ref> and [[Iraq War]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/3660748/ns/politics-tom_curry/t/kerry-warns-cut-run-iraq/#.V1xkd5MrIp8|title=Kerry warns of 'cut and run' in Iraq|last=Curry|first=Tom|date=December 3, 2003|website=|publisher=[[NBC News]]|access-date=June 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/09/28/AR2006092801844.html|title=Bush Attacks Party of 'Cut and Run'|last=Fletcher|first=Michael|date=September 29, 2006|website=|publisher=''[[Washington Post]]''|access-date=June 11, 2016}}</ref> It was also used in similarly in Australia in reference to the Iraq War<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/pm/content/2004/s1073947.htm|title=Cut-and-run or needed exit strategy: Parliament argues over troops|last=Yaxley|first=Louise|date=March 25, 2004|website=|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|access-date=June 11, 2016}}</ref> and the [[War in Afghanistan (2015–present)|2015 War in Afghanistan]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/dont-cut-and-run-from-afghanistan-warns-defence-chief-mark-binskin-20151021-gkf25n.html|title=Don't cut and run from Afghanistan, warns Defence chief Mark Binskin|last=Wroe|first=David|date=October 21, 2015|website=|publisher=''[[Sydney Morning Herald]]''|access-date=June 11, 2016}}</ref> and in Great Britain in reference to the Iraq War.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2004/apr/12/uk.iraq|title=Defeat would be victory for fanatics, says Blair|last=Wintour|first=Patrick|date=April 11, 2004|website=|publisher=''[[The Guardian]]''|access-date=June 11, 2016}}</ref> The phrase was also used during the [[Republican Party presidential debates and forums, 2016|2016 Republican presidential debates]] by [[Jeb Bush]] to describe [[Marco Rubio]] in reference to the [[Gang of Eight (immigration)|Gang of Eight]] and [[History of laws concerning immigration and naturalization in the United States|immigration reform]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/29/us/politics/republican-presidential-debate-transcript.html|title=Transcript of the Main Republican Presidential Debate|last=|first=|date=January 28, 2016|website=|publisher=''[[The New York Times]]''|access-date=June 11, 2016}}</ref>

Variations on the phrase were used by [[Ken Mehlman]], then Chairperson of the United States [[Republican National Committee]], to describe the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party's]] call to withdraw troops from the Iraq War: "Some are saying we need to cut and run, others are saying we need to cut and jog, and still others are saying we need to cut and walk."<ref>{{cite AV media|date= June 20, 2006|title= The Situation Room with Wolf Blitzer|medium= Television production|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0606/20/sitroom.01.html|access-date= June 11, 2016|publisher= [[CNN]]}}</ref>

