==Other languages== [[Italian language|Italian]] is spoken by communities in [[Argentina]], [[Brazil]], [[Chile]], [[Colombia]], [[Uruguay]], [[Peru]], and [[Venezuela]].{{cn|date=June 2018}}
[[German language|German]] is used by some in Brazil, Argentina, Guyana, Suriname, Chile, Colombia, Venezuela, Peru, [[Bolivia]], and [[Paraguay]].{{cn|date=June 2018}}
Speakers of [[Arabic]] (chiefly of [[Lebanon|Lebanese]], [[Demographics of Syria|Syrian]] or [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] descent), are commonly found in parts of in Brazil, Colombia, Guyana, Suriname, Argentina, Paraguay, Chile (largest Palestinian colony outside the Middle East) and Venezuela.{{cn|date=June 2018}}
[[Welsh language|Welsh]] is spoken and written in the historic towns of [[Trelew]] and [[Rawson, Chubut|Rawson]] in the Argentine [[Patagonia]].{{cn|date=June 2018}}
There are small [[Croatian language|Croatian]], [[Greek language|Greek]], [[Polish language|Polish]], [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] and [[Russian language|Russian]]-speaking communities in Brazil, Chile, and Argentina.{{cn|date=June 2018}}
There are also many [[Romani language|Romani]]-speakers, originating in Eastern Europe, throughout South America particularly in Colombia, Chile, Brazil, and Argentina.{{cn|date=June 2018}}
There are Eastern European [[Romanian language|Romanian]] speakers, especially in Argentina, Brazil, Chile and Colombia, where Romanian populations live.{{cn|date=June 2018}}
There are also small clusters of [[Japanese language|Japanese]]-speakers in Brazil, Peru, Bolivia (including [[Okinawan people|Okinawans]] from the island of Okinawa), Colombia, Paraguay, and Ecuador. Brazil currently holds the largest Japanese community outside Japan <ref name=japantimes>{{cite web |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/nn20080115i1.html |title=Japan, Brazil mark a century of settlement, family ties <nowiki>|</nowiki> The Japan Times Online |date=2008-01-15}}</ref>
[[Caribbean Hindustani|Hindustani]] and other [[Languages of India|Indian languages]] are commonly found in [[Guyana]], [[Suriname]], and [[French Guiana]].{{cn|date=June 2018}}
[[Javanese language|Javanese]] is commonly found in [[Guyana]], [[Suriname]], and [[French Guiana]].{{cn|date=June 2018}}
The [[Rapa Nui Language]] is a [[Polynesian languages|Polynesian]] origin found in [[Easter Island]], Chile and [[Maori language|Maori]] is also found in Easter Island.{{cn|date=June 2018}}
Most South American countries mandate the regular study of one or more of English, French, German or Italian. These countries often have advanced cultural language institutes for those respective languages centered in their major cities.{{cn|date=June 2018}}
In Brazil, Italian and German dialects, specifically [[Talian dialect|Talian]], [[East Pomeranian dialect|East Pomeranian]] and [[Riograndenser Hunsrückisch]], have co-official status alongside [[Portuguese Language|Portuguese]] in about a dozen cities, and are mandatory subjects in schools in other municipalities. Brazil's largest city [[Sao Paulo]] has large numbers of German, Italian, Japanese and [[Levantine Arabic]] speakers.{{cn|date=June 2018}}
