{{distinguish|Nyika language|Nyika languages}} {{Infobox language |name=Nyiha |nativename=''Ishinyiha'' |states=[[Tanzania]], [[Zambia]], [[Malawi]] |ethnicity=[[Nyiha people|Nyiha]] |speakers=670,000 |date=1987–1993 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo languages|Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Benue–Congo languages|Benue–Congo]] |fam4=[[Bantoid languages|Bantoid]] |fam5=[[Bantu languages|Bantu]] |fam6=[[Rukwa languages|Rukwa]] |fam7=Mbozi |fam8=Mbeya |fam9=South |lc1=nih|ld1=(Tanzania, Zambia) |lc2=nyr|ld2=(Malawi) |glotto=mboz1234 |glottorefname=Mbozi–Malawi Nyika |guthrie=M.23 }}
'''Nyiha''' (Nyixa, Nyika) is a [[Bantu languages|Bantu language]] primarily spoken in Tanzania and Zambia. The language of the 10,000 speakers in Malawi is different enough to sometimes be considered a distinct language.
