'''Thomas King Ekundayo Phillips''' (1884 – 10 July 1969) was a Nigerian organist, conductor, composer and teacher who has been described as the "father of Nigerian church music"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com.ng/books?id=42kbAQAAMAAJ&q=|title=The Oxford Companion to Black British History|author1=David Dabydeen|author2=John Gilmore|author3=Cecily Jones|publisher=Pennsylvania State University (Oxford University Press)|year=2008|isbn=978-0-199-2389-41|page=463}}</ref>

==Life==

Thomas Ekundayo Phillips was born in 1884.{{sfn|Agordoh|2005|p=130}}
His father was Bishop [[Charles Phillips (bishop)|Charles Phillips]] of [[Ondo State|Ondo]].{{sfn|Peel|2003|p=387}}
He attended the [[CMS Grammar School, Lagos]], then went to the Government Training School for Dispensers, where he qualified as a Chemist.{{sfn|Agordoh|2005|p=130}}
He became an optician by profession.{{sfn|Motunrayo Joel|2014}}
Phillips was encouraged to study music by the Archdeacon Nathaniel, his uncle.{{sfn|Agordoh|2005|p=130}}
His uncle Johnson Phillips, an Anglican priest, gave him his first organ lessons.{{sfn|Godwin Sadoh|2008}}
Solomon Moses Daniels, a well-known organist at Saint Paul's Church, Aroloya, gave him lessons in organ playing.
He was Assistant Organist at Saint Paul's Church, Lagos until 1914.{{sfn|Agordoh|2005|p=130}}

Phillips attended [[Trinity College of Music]] in London from 1911 to 1914, where he studied organ, piano and violin.{{sfn|Sadoh|2007}}
He was given the Fellowship of Trinity College of Music, London (FTCML) in organ playing,{{sfn|Agordoh|2005|p=130}}
Phillips was the second Nigerian to obtain a baccalaureate degree in music.{{sfn|Michael Olutayo Olatunji|2005|p=11}}
When he returned to Nigeria in 1914 Bishop [[Herbert Tugwell]] invited Phillips to become organist and Master of the Music at the [[Cathedral Church of Christ, Lagos]].
{{sfn|Agordoh|2005|p=130}}
He would retain this position for 48 years.{{sfn|Sadoh|2007}}
His elder brother became bishop of the cathedral, the second African bishop there after Archbishop [[Leslie Vining]].{{sfn|Motunrayo Joel|2014}}

Phillips trained well-known students such as [[Fela Sowande]], [[Ayo Bankole]], [[Lazarus Ekwueme]], Christopher Oyesiku and his son Charles Oluwole Obayomi Phillips, who succeeded him at the Cathedral Church of Christ.{{sfn|Sadoh|2007}}
Fela Sowande always remembered the training that Phillips provided, which was a great help in his own career.{{sfn|Fela Sowande  (1905-1987), AfriClassical.com}}
In 1964 the [[University of Nigeria, Nsukka]] awarded Phillips an honorary Doctor of Music degree for his contributions to development of Nigerian church music.{{sfn|Godwin Sadoh|2008}}
Phillips died on 10 July 1969.{{sfn|Agordoh|2005|p=131}}
He had five children.{{sfn|Motunrayo Joel|2014}}

==Work==

In 1926 Phillips presented a proposal to the Synod of the Diocese of Lagos, which was accepted, to use "native airs" in church services.{{sfn|Peel|2003|p=387}}
Most of his work consisted of church music that included hymns, antiphonal chants, choral anthems in [[Yoruba language]] and two organ solo works, Passacaglia on an African Folk Song and Variations on an African Folk Song.{{sfn|Sadoh|2007}}
Phillips wrote three short organ solo compositions, but most of his organ pieces were based on existing indigenous themes.{{sfn|Sadoh|2008|p=3}}
He made the first modern arrangement of ''Ise Oluwa'', the most popular Yoruba Christian hymn, for [[SATB]] with organ accompaniment.{{sfn|Sadoh|2008|p=53}}
Phillips was the author of ''Yoruba Music'' (Johannesburg: African Music Society, 1953), the first musicological treatise by a trained African musician to discuss African music. 
The book describes Yoruba traditional music in detail and shows how the concepts in this indigenous tradition can be incorporated in modern works.{{sfn|Sadoh|2007}}

